# Deprecated Aigentron releases — one per line, format: X.Y.Z: reason
#
# What this does: install.sh's warn_if_deprecated() fetches this file (from
# the PUBLIC repo's `main` via raw.githubusercontent.com, or its S3 mirror in
# S3 mode) and prints a warning — never a hard block — if the version being
# installed is listed here. This only covers an explicit `VERSION=x.y.z`
# pin; "latest" auto-resolution is already covered by the mechanism below
# and never needs an entry here. (infra/update-check.sh does not consume
# this file today — it only compares installed-vs-latest.)
#
# Not instant: this file lives in the PRIVATE dev repo. A commit here only
# reaches the PUBLIC repo's `main` (what install.sh actually fetches) via
# publish/sync-public.sh, which only runs as part of cutting a release (a
# tag push). In practice that's fine — the normal remedy for "this release
# is bad" is shipping the next one anyway, and that release's own workflow
# run is what makes the new DEPRECATED entry live.
#
# How to deprecate a release (two-part — do both, then cut a release so it
# actually reaches the public repo/S3):
#   1. Hide it from "latest" auto-resolution (GitHub mode only — S3 mode's
#      `latest.txt` is just a mutable pointer; keep it always correct
#      manually and skip this step):
#        gh release edit vX.Y.Z --repo <owner>/<public-repo> --prerelease
#   2. Protect explicit `VERSION=X.Y.Z` pins: add a line below, commit to
#      `main`, and cut a release (any version) — that release's workflow
#      run mirrors this file to the public repo and to S3 (release.yml).
#
# Never remove/reuse a version's own release — this file only marks it,
# doesn't unpublish it (matches this repo's "never reuse a tag" rule).

0.1.0: published release archive was missing tsconfig.base.json (publish/allowlist.txt gap since the release tooling's first commit) — every from-source build fails with TS5083 (bare-metal mode didn't exist yet — Docker mode only). Fixed in 0.1.3.
0.1.1: same tsconfig.base.json gap as 0.1.0 (still unfixed at this point), PLUS install.sh hard-required Docker with no bare-metal alternative, and REPO defaulted to an unfilled CHANGEME/aigentron placeholder, breaking every fresh install that didn't pass REPO= explicitly — fixed in 0.1.2/0.1.3.
0.1.2: same tsconfig.base.json gap as 0.1.0/0.1.1 (fails with TS5083 before bare-metal mode — new in this version — even gets a chance to run), PLUS infra/minimal-entrypoint.sh was tracked in git without its executable bit, so any build that got past tsconfig would crash-loop under systemd (203/EXEC "Permission denied"). Docker mode only hit the tsconfig bug (its Dockerfile chmod +x's the entrypoint itself). Tsconfig fixed in 0.1.3, executable bit fixed in 0.1.7.
0.1.3: tsconfig fixed, but bare-metal mode checked only that python3 existed (not that its venv/ensurepip module worked — breaks on Debian/Ubuntu where that's a separate, sometimes version-specific package like python3.14-venv), PLUS the same missing-executable-bit bug as 0.1.2 — bare-metal installs fail one way or the other regardless of which bug is hit first. Docker mode unaffected by either. Python3-venv fixed in 0.1.4, executable bit fixed in 0.1.7.
0.1.4: python3-venv fixed, but the missing-executable-bit bug (see 0.1.2) was still present — every bare-metal install crash-loops under systemd with 203/EXEC. Docker mode unaffected. Fixed in 0.1.7.
0.1.5: same missing-executable-bit bug as 0.1.2-0.1.4 (still unfixed at this point) — every bare-metal install crash-loops with systemd 203/EXEC. Docker mode unaffected. Fixed in 0.1.7.
0.1.6: same missing-executable-bit bug as 0.1.2-0.1.5 (still unfixed at this point) — every bare-metal install crash-loops with systemd 203/EXEC. Docker mode unaffected. Fixed in 0.1.7.
0.1.7: infra/setup-wizard.mjs and scripts/cli-auth.sh both ran `claude setup-token` with its stdout piped/captured (to auto-scrape the printed token) — this hides the interactive login URL from the operator, so the command hangs forever waiting for a browser confirmation nobody could see how to give. Same bug present in every earlier version that shipped either file (back to 0.1.1) — only oauth-token onboarding via the automatic path is affected, not core install/build. Both now run with fully inherited stdio and prompt for a manual paste instead. Fixed in 0.1.8.
0.1.9: the wizard's Kind-guessing heuristic (and the pre-existing server/dashboard copies it mirrored) assumed any `api.deepseek.com` URL wanted kind=deepseek, and printed active guidance telling operators a base URL ending in `/anthropic` was wrong for a non-anthropic kind — but some vendors (DeepSeek confirmed) expose a real, documented Anthropic-protocol-compatible path of their own (`https://api.deepseek.com/anthropic`), for which kind=anthropic is correct. This actively steered operators away from a legitimate, working setup. Fixed in 0.1.10: the heuristic now recognizes a `.../anthropic` URL suffix (any vendor) and suggests kind=anthropic for it; the misleading blanket warning was replaced with one that only fires on an actual mismatch with the suggestion.
0.1.10: infra/setup-wizard.mjs's masked-input prompt (used for every secret/token field) called `rl.question('', cb)` plus a manual redraw on each keystroke to fake password masking — but readline's own internal line-refresh runs even with an empty prompt string, wiping the just-printed field label right after it appears; it then only reappears once the first keystroke triggers the manual redraw. Visually this looks like "the field doesn't appear until you start typing" — a real, reproducible bug (confirmed by a stray `[K` escape-sequence artifact visible in this codebase's own earlier test transcripts), present since the wizard was first shipped (0.1.1). Fixed in 0.1.11: rewritten to do raw single-character accumulation directly (pausing the shared readline interface for the duration), the standard password-prompt pattern, with no interaction with readline's internal refresh at all.
